<subsection xml:id="subsec-evaluating-algebraic-expressions-by-substitution">
    <title>Evaluating algebraic expressions by substitution</title>
    <p>
        We often deal with formulas and expressions on our day-to-day calculations. For example, calculating the total cost of items, determining the speed of a moving object, or finding the area of a piece of land. These formulas use letters (variables) to represent unknown values. In this section, we will learn how to evaluate algebraic expressions by replacing variables with given numbers.
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <m>Naree</m> Bus company charges <m>60 m + 150</m> shillings for a trip to town, where <m>m</m> is the number of kilometres travelled. Find the total cost for a <m>7 km</m> trip.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Here we are given <m>m</m> = <m>7</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                Therefore,
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    
                60 m + 150 = 60 (7) + 150
                </me>
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    = 420 + 150
                </me>
            </p>
            <p>
                <me>
                    = 570 shillings
                </me>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                On a market day at Malava market, the cost of a bunch of <m>Sukuma</m> <m>wiki</m> is <m>t</m> shillings, a <m>gorogoro</m> of maize is <m>y</m> shillings and a tomato is <m>z</m> shillings.
            </p>
            <p>
                [**Aphoto of a marker with sukuma wiki and maize bag with the price tags**]
            </p>
            <p>
                Write Expressions when:
            </p>
            <p>
                <ul>
